  field_id:"unpackedSogoRunnyMixtureSoluteHardInstruction",
  instruction:"Some glazes can naturally deflocculate (thinn). A side effect of this is that the glaze no longer holds its suspension well. It quickly sinks to the bottom of the bucket. If left unused for a long time, the ingredients can form a hard layer that you can no longer stir.

  Pour the water into a clean bucket and scrape off the hard cake with a scraper. Slowly add the glaze chunks to the water in the other bucket and stir or mix thoroughly. Measure the specific gravity and viscosity. The glaze may need to be thickened with Epsom salts. This will prevent it from settling, making it easier to stir next time.",
  section_id:{{section_id }}
%}

{%
  render 'radio-fields',
  field_id:"unpackedSogoRunnyMixtureSolutePebbleInstruction",
  instruction:"If you don't use a glaze for a while, it can crystallize slightly, especially due to temperature fluctuations. These crystals are recognizable as small grains or pebbles in the glaze. Strain the glaze and collect the small grains. Scrape them out of the strainer and place them in a small jar. Fill it with a small amount of hot water. The grains will dissolve. Add this solution back to the glaze.",
  section_id:{{section_id }}
%}

{%
  render 'radio-fields',
  field_id:"unpackedSogoRunnyMixtureSoluteSurfaceInstruction",
  instruction:"Een gebarsten glazuurlaag betekent altijd een te dik gelegde glazuurlaag. Dat kan drie oorzaken hebben:

  het soortelijk gewicht van het glazuur is te hoog

  de viscositeit van het glazuur is te hoog (doorlooptijd te lang)

  de contacttijd van het glazuur met de biscuit gebakken scherf is te lang

  Controleer dus zeker het soortelijk gewicht en de viscositeit. Als deze in orde zijn, probeer sneller te werken. De biscuitbaktemperatuur verhogen kan ook helpen bij zeer poreuze kleisoorten die veel water aanzuigen. ",
  section_id:{{section_id }}
%}

{%
