{%
  render 'radio-fields',
  field_id:"backedDroppedInstruction",
  instruction:"
  A glaze drips in one or more of these cases:

  the glaze has been applied too thickly to the shard by keeping it in contact with the biscuit-fired shard for too long or by brushing on too many layers

  the glaze is too viscous, so it was applied too thickly to the shard

  the specific gravity of the glaze is too high

  the glaze was fired too high.

  Be sure to check the specific gravity and viscosity. These should match the packaging. Glaze quickly and efficiently, and don't layer too many layers. Monitor your kiln's heat output using melting cones.
  ",
  section_id:{{section_id }}
%}

{%
  render 'radio-fields',
  field_id:"backedNotColoredInstruction",
  instruction:"
  Most SOGO glazes are vibrant, multi-shaded. These glazes look completely different depending on how thin or thick they are. For example, Pacific Blue turns brown if applied too thinly and orange-yellow if applied very thickly, with a variety of blue shades in between.

  Always check the specific gravity and viscosity before glazing. Get to know the specific glaze. Perform tests with short and long contact times to determine the possible color variations.

  Be sure to check out the photos of the glaze in question in the webshop. They show examples of thin versus thick glaze layers.

  The clay used also plays a significant role in the color development. Some glazes look completely different on red clay compared to white. An example of this is shown in the webshop for each glaze.
  ",
  section_id:{{section_id }}
%}

{%
  render 'radio-fields',
  field_id:"backedMatteInstruction",
  instruction:"
  A glossy glaze only shines when it's sufficiently melted. Is your glaze matte? Then it hasn't received enough heat work. SOGO glazes are ideally fired on melting cone 7. Monitor the firing with melting cones. Place cones on all levels of the kiln.

  A glaze can also be dull if it's applied too thinly. You'll then actually see and feel the underlying shard. In that case, be sure to check the specific gravity and viscosity and adjust as needed. Apply sufficient layers or adjust the contact time between the glaze and the shard.
  ",
  section_id:{{section_id }}
%}

{%
  render 'radio-fields',
  field_id:"backedCrawledInstruction",
  instruction:"
  Glazes creep away when they:

  be laid on too thick

  the specific gravity is too high

  the viscosity is too high

  It is more common on flat items such as plates or the bottom of bowls and dishes.

  Be sure to check the specific gravity and viscosity. Glaze smoothly and efficiently. Don't let the glaze remain in contact with the shard for too long.
  ",
  section_id:{{section_id }}
%}

